04368nam a2200649Ia 9780801470875DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20142015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014708757 a10.7591/97808014708752doi  a(DE-B1597)496490  a(OCoLC)881436757  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a327.732231 aPosen, Barry R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRestraint :bA New Foundation for U.S. Grand Strategy /cBarry R. Posen. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b8 tables, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables and Maps -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Evolution of Post–Cold War -- t1. The Perils of Liberal Hegemony -- t2. The Case for Restraint -- t3. Command of the Commons: The Military Strategy -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe United States, Barry R. Posen argues in Restraint, has grown incapable of moderating its ambitions in international politics. Since the collapse of Soviet power, it has pursued a grand strategy that he calls "liberal hegemony," one that Posen sees as unnecessary, counterproductive, costly, and wasteful. Written for policymakers and observers alike, Restraint explains precisely why this grand strategy works poorly and then provides a carefully designed alternative grand strategy and an associated military strategy and force structure. In contrast to the failures and unexpected problems that have stemmed from America’s consistent overreaching, Posen makes an urgent argument for restraint in the future use of U.S. military strength. After setting out the political implications of restraint as a guiding principle, Posen sketches the appropriate military forces and posture that would support such a strategy. He works with a deliberately constrained notion of grand strategy and, even more important, of national security (which he defines as including sovereignty, territorial integrity, power position, and safety). His alternative for military strategy, which Posen calls "command of the commons," focuses on protecting U.S. global access through naval, air, and space power, while freeing the United States from most of the relationships that require the permanent stationing of U.S. forces overseas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aElectronic books. 0aHegemonyzUnited States. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aUnited States, grand strategy, US military strength, American national security strategy, security affairs, international politics, collapse of Soviet power, liberal hegemony, military strategy, force structure, global power, American national interests.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147087540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470875423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470875/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles